# GitHub Authentication with Personal Access Token (PAT)
When you push code from Git to GitHub, you can no longer use your GitHub password. Instead, you must use a Personal Access Token (PAT) as the password. This is more secure and required by GitHub.

Create a Personal Access Token (PAT)
1 . Go to GitHub
2 . Click your profile picture → Settings
3 . Open Developer settings
4 . Click Personal access tokens
5 . Select Tokens (classic) → Generate new token
6 . Give a name like git-access
7 . Set expiration 
8 . Select permissions:
9 . Click Generate token
10 . Copy the token immediately (you cannot see it again)

# Use PAT When Pushing Code
git push origin main
Username: your-github-username
Password: <paste your PAT here>
👉 Paste the token instead of your GitHub password
